  | publisher = Lit\n  | location= Berlin, Germany\n  | isbn = 978-3-643-10820-3\n  | pages = 119\u2013146\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Senocak\n  | first = Neslihan\n  | year = 2012\n  | title = The Poor and the Perfect: the Rise of Learning in the Franciscan Order, 1209\u20131310\n  | publisher = Cornell University Press\n  | location= New York City\n  | isbn = 978-0-8014-6471-3\n  | url =\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Spufford\n  | first = Peter\n  | year = 1989\n  | title = Money and its Use in Medieval Europe\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  | location= Cambridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-521-37590-0\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Stacey\n  | first = Robert C.\n  | editor-last=Prestwich\n  | editor-first=Michael\n  | editor2-last=Britnell\n  | editor2-first=Richard H.\n  | editor3-last=Frame\n  | editor3-first=Robin\n  | year = 1997\n  | chapter = Parliamentary Negotiation and the Expulsion of the Jews from England\n  | title = Thirteenth Century England: Proceedings of the Durham Conference, 1995\n  | volume = 6\n  | publisher = Boydell Press\n  | location= Woodbridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-85115-674-3\n  | pages = 77\u2013102\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Stacey\n  | first = Robert C.\n  | editor-last= Skinner\n  | editor-first= Patricia\n  | year = 2003\n  | chapter = The English Jews Under Henry III: Historical, Literary and Archaeological Perspectives\n  | title = Jews in Medieval Britain\n  | publisher = Boydell Press\n  | location= Woodbridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-1-84383-733-6\n  | pages = 41\u201354\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Turner\n  | first = Ralph V.\n  | year = 2009\n  | title = King John: England's Evil King?\n  | publisher = History Press\n  | location= Stroud, UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-7524-4850-3\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Tyerman\n  | first = Christopher\n  | authorlink = Christopher Tyerman\n  | year = 1996\n  | title = England and the Crusades, 1095\u20131588\n  | publisher = University of Chicago Press\n  | location= Chicago, US\n  | isbn = 978-0-226-82013-2\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Vincent\n  | first = Nicholas\n  | year = 2006\n  | title = The Holy Blood: King Henry III and the Westminster Blood Relic\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  | location= Cambridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-521-02660-4\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Vincent\n  | first = Nicholas\n  | editor-last=Church\n  | editor-first=Stephen D.\n  | year = 2007\n  | chapter = Isabella of Angoul\u00eame: John's Jezebel\n  | title = King John: New Interpretations\n  | publisher = Boydell Press\n  | location= Woodbridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-85115-947-8\n  | pages = 165\u2013219\n  | ref= harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Warren\n  | first = W. Lewis\n  | year = 1991\n  | title = King John\n  | publisher = Methuen\n  | location= London, UK\n  | isbn = 0-413-45520-3\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Weiler\n  | first = Bj\u00f6rn K. U.\n  | editor-last=Prestwich\n  | editor-first=Michael\n  | editor2-last=Britnell\n  | editor2-first=Richard\n  | editor3-last=Frame\n  | editor3-first=Robin\n  | year = 1999\n  | chapter = Henry III's Plans for a German Marriage and their Context\n  | title = Thirteenth Century England: Proceedings of the Durham Conference, 1997\n  | volume = 7\n  | publisher = Boydell Press\n  | location= Woodbridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-85115-719-1\n  | pages = 173\u2013188\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Weiler\n  | first = Bj\u00f6rn K. U.\n  | year = 2012\n  | title = Henry III of England and the Staufen Empire, 1216\u20131272\n  | edition =\n  | publisher = Royal Historical Society: Boydell Press\n  | location= Paris\n  | isbn = 978-0-86193-319-8\n  | url =\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Wild\n  | first = Benjamin L.\n  | editor1-last=Burton\n  | editor1-first=Janet E.\n  | editor2-last=Lachaud\n  | editor2-first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique\n  | editor3-last=Schofield\n  | editor3-first=Phillipp R.\n  | editor4-last=St\u00f6ber\n  | editor4-first=Karen\n  | editor5-last=Weiler\n  | editor5-first=Bj\u00f6rn K.\n  | year = 2011\n  | chapter = A Captive King: Henry III Between the Battles of Lewes and Evesham 1264-5\n  | title = Thirteenth Century England: Proceedings of the Paris Conference 2009\n  | volume = 13\n  | publisher = Boydell Press\n  | location= Woodbridge, UK\n  | isbn = 978-1-84383-618-6\n  | pages = 41\u201356\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Plantagenet]]|1 October|1207|16 November|1272}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John, King of England|John]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Kingdom of England|King of England]]<br>[[Duke of Aquitaine]]<br>[[Lordship of Ireland|Lord of Ireland]]|years=1216\u20131272}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward I of England|Edward I]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{House of Plantagenet|edward1|Royal Arms of England (1198-1340).svg}}\n{{English monarchs}}\n{{Norman Dukes}}\n\n{{Subject bar|portal2=England|portal3=Biography|portal4=Middle Ages|portal5=Monarchy |commons=y }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henry 03 Of England}}\n[[Category:1207 births]]\n[[Category:1272 deaths]]\n[[Category:13th-century English monarchs]]\n[[Category:13th-century peers of France]]<!--as Duke of Aquitaine-->\n[[Category:Henry III of England| ]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Normandy]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:House of Plantagenet]]\n[[Category:Medieval child rulers]]\n[[Category:People from Winchester]]\n[[Category:People of the Barons' Wars]]\n", "name_user": "Jc3s5h", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove duplicate date template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_III_of_England"}
{"title_page": "Panashe Chigumadzi", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Panashe Chigumadzi\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Panashe Chigumadzi - TEDxSoweto 2014.jpg\n| caption            = Panashe Chigumadzi - TEDxSoweto 2014\n| birth_place        = Zimbabwe\n| education          = Harvard Univeristy - doctoral student\n| alma_mater         = University of the Witwatersand\n| notable_works      = ''These Bones Will Rise Again''\n| website            = www.panashechigumadzi.com\n}}\n\n'''Panashe Chigumadzi''' is a [[Zimbabwe|Zimbabwean]] journalist, essayist and novelist.\n\n==Career==\nChigumadzi has published her writing in a variety of media. She is a columnist for ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/jul/29/books-about-zimbabwe-panashe-chigumadzi|title=Panashe Chigumadzi picks the best books about Zimbabwe|last=Chigumadzi|first=Panashe|date=2018-07-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> ''[[Die Zeit]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[New York Review of Books]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2017/11/09/soap-and-south-africas-fatal-intimacy/|title=Soap and South Africa's 'Fatal Intimacy'|last=Chigumadzi|first=Panashe|date=2017-11-09|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/contributors/panashe-chigumadzi/|title=Panashe Chigumadzi|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and ''[[Chimurenga (magazine)|Chimurenga]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/prj/kwe/en/program/guests/21524367.html|title=Panashe Chigumadzi|website=@GI_weltweit|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> She was a founder of ''VANGUARD'', a magazine designed to give space to young, black South African women interested in how queer identities, pan-Africanism and Black Consciousness intersect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vanguardmagazine.co.za/about/|title=VANGUARD|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925171414/http://vanguardmagazine.co.za/about/|archive-date=31 May 2014|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> At the start of her career, Chigumadzi worked as a reporter for [[CNBC Africa]].<ref>{{Citation|title=A new self-identity for Africans {{!}} Panashe Chigumadzi {{!}} TEDxJohannesburg|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hemD116ipcg|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> \n\nChigumadzi draws on the history of Zimbabwe in her work, by exploring national and personal histories and identities. Her 2017 narrative essay ''These Bones Will Rise Again'' drew on [[Shona people|Shona]] perspectives to explore the concept of the 'Mothers of the Nation' and interrogating perceptions of [[Nehanda Charwe Nyakasikana]] in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2018/08/06/novuyo-rosa-tshuma-and-panashe-chigumadzi-in-conversation-meditations-on-the-traumas-and-triumphs-of-zimbabwes-histories/|title=Novuyo Rosa Tshuma and Panashe Chigumadzi in conversation\u2014Meditations on the traumas and triumphs of Zimbabwe's histories|date=2018-08-06|website=The Johannesburg Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> \n\nWhile studying and writing the legacies of Zimbabwe's struggle for independence, Chigumadzi also writes about modern identities for southern Africans. She has written on the complexities of identity dismantling the notion of a colourblind, post-Apartheid South Africa, through a reclamation of the term \"coconut\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/24/south-africa-race-panashe-chigumadzi-ruth-first-lecture|title=Why I call myself a 'coconut' to claim my place in post-apartheid South Africa|last=Chigumadzi|first=Panashe|date=2015-08-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She is outspoken about the need for decolonisation at national and at personal levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lucas.leeds.ac.uk/article/unholy-trinity-and-transformation-in-post-1994-south-africa-refocusing-transformation-in-higher-education-for-social-and-economic-empowerment/|title='Unholy Trinity' and 'Transformation' in Post-1994 South Africa: Refocusing 'Transformation' in Higher Education for Social and Economic Empowerment : Centre for African Studies (LUCAS)|website=lucas.leeds.ac.uk|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> Her 2019 essay \"Why I'm No Longer Talking to Nigerians About Race\" discussed her experience at the [[Ak\u00e9 Arts and Book Festival]] on a panel discussing whether [[Black Lives Matter]] has relevance in Africa. Chigumadzi argued that, yes, in a continent with such different experiences of racialisation under colonialism, it did.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africasacountry.com/2019/04/why-im-no-longer-talking-to-nigerians-about-race|title=Why I'm no longer talking to Nigerians about race.|website=africasacountry.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Chigumadzi was Programme Curator of the first Abantu Book Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2016/08/18/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-abantu-book-festival/|title=Everything you need to know about the Abantu Book Festival|website=Sunday Times Books LIVE @ Sunday Times Books LIVE|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> In addition to her writing on literature and literary criticism, she regularly appears on [[BBC World Service]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3csyn9m|title=BBC World Service - The Cultural Frontline, African writers now: Panashe Chigumadzi and Chigozie Obioma|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> She is also a contributor to the 2019 anthology ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]'', edited by [[Margaret Busby]].<ref>Magwood, Michele (2019-07-05), [https://www.wantedonline.co.za/navigator/leisure/2019-07-05-new-daughters-of-africa-is-a-powerful-collection-of-writing-by-women-from-the-continent/ \"'New Daughters of Africa' Is a Powerful Collection of Writing by Women from the Continent\"], ''Wanted''.</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''These Bones Will Rise Again'' (Indigo Books, 2017) \u2013 a mixture of memoir and historical essay exploring nation-building in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theindigopress.com/these-bones-will-rise-again|title=These Bones Will Rise Again|website=The Indigo Press|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n*''Sweet Medicine'' (Blackbird Books, 2015) \u2013 a novel exploring the 2008 economic crisis in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afripopmag.com/2015/10/19/excerpt-zimbabwean-writer-panashe-chigumadzis-debut-novel-sweet-medicine/|title=AfriPop! - What's New and Whats Next in Global African Culture|date=2015-10-19|website=AfriPop! - What's New and Whats Next in Global African Culture|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n*''Beautiful Hair for Landless People'' (forthcoming)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iwp.uiowa.edu/writers/panashe-chikumadzi|title=CHIGUMADZI, Panashe {{!}} The International Writing Program|website=iwp.uiowa.edu|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n* [[K. Sello Duiker]] Literary Prize in 2016 for ''Sweet Medicine''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2019/04/remembering-k-sello-duiker-great-writer-of-south-africas-post-apartheid-generation-who-would-have-been-45-this-month/|title=Remembering K Sello Duiker, Great Writer of South Africa's Post-Apartheid Generation, Who Would Have Been 45 This Month|date=2019-04-19|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n* [[Ruth First]] Journalism Fellowship, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://witsvuvuzela.com/2015/08/14/a-racy-topic-for-ruth-first/|title=A racy topic for Ruth First|last=Dzonzi|first=Thembisile|date=2015-08-14|website=Wits Vuvuzela|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Reception ===\nChigumadzi's work has been studied widely, particularly within post-colonial studies. Her writing on the use of charms in ''Sweet Medicine'' led to further studies on healthcare and traditional practices in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stobie|first=Cheryl|date=2018-07-03|title=Charms, Blessings and Compromises: Black Women's Bodies and Decolonization in Panashe Chigumadzi's Sweet Medicine|journal=English Academy Review|volume=35|issue=2|pages=37\u201353|doi=10.1080/10131752.2018.1523983|issn=1013-1752}}</ref> Her focus on strong female characters living in economic precarity has been explored in terms of their religious beliefs and the reflection they may give to contemporary life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ndlovu|first=Isaac|date=2016-07-02|title=Politically induced economic precarity, syncretism and female representations in Chigumadzi's Sweet Medicine|journal=Agenda|volume=30|issue=3|pages=96\u2013103|doi=10.1080/10130950.2016.1251227|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nChigumadzi was born in Zimbabwe and grew up in South Africa. She studied at [[University of the Witwatersrand|University of the Witwatersrand;]] while there she was part of the \"Transform Wits Movement\", which called for significant changes to southern Africa's universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailyvox.co.za/transform-wits-lower-tuition-fees-change-of-curriculum-and-better-treatment-of-workers/|title=Transform Wits: lower tuition fees, change of curriculum and better treatment of workers|last=Pilane|first=Pontsho|date=2015-04-13|website=The Daily Vox|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> As part of her doctoral study at the Hutchins Center for African and African American Research at [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africa.harvard.edu/event/symposium-writing-beyond-mugabes-zimbabwe|title=Symposium: Writing Beyond \"Mugabe's Zimbabwe\"|website=africa.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> she has written about the [[Rhodes Must Fall]] protests she witnessed at University of the Witwatersrand.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Panashe Chigumadzi|date=2016|title=Small Deaths|journal=Transition|issue=121|pages=148\u2013163|doi=10.2979/transition.121.1.26|jstor=10.2979/transition.121.1.26}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n[http://www.panashechigumadzi.com/bio Panashe Chigumadzi website]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chigumadzi, Panashe}}\n[[Category:Women writers (modern period)]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean writers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Panashe Chigumadzi\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Panashe Chigumadzi - TEDxSoweto 2014.jpg\n| caption            = Panashe Chigumadzi - TEDxSoweto 2014\n| birth_place        = Zimbabwe\n| education          = Harvard Univeristy - doctoral student\n| alma_mater         = University of the Witwatersand\n| notable_works      = ''These Bones Will Rise Again''\n| website            = www.panashechigumadzi.com\n}}\n\n'''Panashe Chigumadzi''' is a [[Zimbabwe|Zimbabwean]] journalist, essayist and novelist.\n\n==Career==\nChigumadzi has published her writing in a variety of media. She is a columnist for ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/jul/29/books-about-zimbabwe-panashe-chigumadzi|title=Panashe Chigumadzi picks the best books about Zimbabwe|last=Chigumadzi|first=Panashe|date=2018-07-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> ''[[Die Zeit]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[New York Review of Books]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2017/11/09/soap-and-south-africas-fatal-intimacy/|title=Soap and South Africa's 'Fatal Intimacy'|last=Chigumadzi|first=Panashe|date=2017-11-09|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/contributors/panashe-chigumadzi/|title=Panashe Chigumadzi|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and ''[[Chimurenga (magazine)|Chimurenga]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/prj/kwe/en/program/guests/21524367.html|title=Panashe Chigumadzi|website=@GI_weltweit|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> She was a founder of ''VANGUARD'', a magazine designed to give space to young, black South African women interested in how queer identities, pan-Africanism and Black Consciousness intersect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vanguardmagazine.co.za/about/|title=VANGUARD|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925171414/http://vanguardmagazine.co.za/about/|archive-date=31 May 2014|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> At the start of her career, Chigumadzi worked as a reporter for [[CNBC Africa]].<ref>{{Citation|title=A new self-identity for Africans {{!}} Panashe Chigumadzi {{!}} TEDxJohannesburg|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hemD116ipcg|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> \n\nChigumadzi draws on the history of Zimbabwe in her work, by exploring national and personal histories and identities. Her 2017 narrative essay ''These Bones Will Rise Again'' drew on [[Shona people|Shona]] perspectives to explore the concept of the 'Mothers of the Nation' and interrogating perceptions of [[Nehanda Charwe Nyakasikana]] in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2018/08/06/novuyo-rosa-tshuma-and-panashe-chigumadzi-in-conversation-meditations-on-the-traumas-and-triumphs-of-zimbabwes-histories/|title=Novuyo Rosa Tshuma and Panashe Chigumadzi in conversation\u2014Meditations on the traumas and triumphs of Zimbabwe's histories|date=2018-08-06|website=The Johannesburg Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> \n\nWhile studying and writing the legacies of Zimbabwe's struggle for independence, Chigumadzi also writes about modern identities for southern Africans. She has written on the complexities of identity dismantling the notion of a colourblind, post-Apartheid South Africa, through a reclamation of the term \"coconut\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/24/south-africa-race-panashe-chigumadzi-ruth-first-lecture|title=Why I call myself a 'coconut' to claim my place in post-apartheid South Africa|last=Chigumadzi|first=Panashe|date=2015-08-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She is outspoken about the need for decolonisation at national and at personal levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lucas.leeds.ac.uk/article/unholy-trinity-and-transformation-in-post-1994-south-africa-refocusing-transformation-in-higher-education-for-social-and-economic-empowerment/|title='Unholy Trinity' and 'Transformation' in Post-1994 South Africa: Refocusing 'Transformation' in Higher Education for Social and Economic Empowerment : Centre for African Studies (LUCAS)|website=lucas.leeds.ac.uk|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> Her 2019 essay \"Why I'm No Longer Talking to Nigerians About Race\" discussed her experience at the [[Ak\u00e9 Arts and Book Festival]] on a panel discussing whether [[Black Lives Matter]] has relevance in Africa. Chigumadzi argued that, yes, in a continent with such different experiences of racialisation under colonialism, it did.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africasacountry.com/2019/04/why-im-no-longer-talking-to-nigerians-about-race|title=Why I'm no longer talking to Nigerians about race.|website=africasacountry.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Chigumadzi was Programme Curator of the first Abantu Book Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2016/08/18/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-abantu-book-festival/|title=Everything you need to know about the Abantu Book Festival|website=Sunday Times Books LIVE @ Sunday Times Books LIVE|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> In addition to her writing on literature and literary criticism, she regularly appears on [[BBC World Service]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3csyn9m|title=BBC World Service - The Cultural Frontline, African writers now: Panashe Chigumadzi and Chigozie Obioma|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> She is also a contributor to the 2019 anthology ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]'', edited by [[Margaret Busby]].<ref>Magwood, Michele (2019-07-05), [https://www.wantedonline.co.za/navigator/leisure/2019-07-05-new-daughters-of-africa-is-a-powerful-collection-of-writing-by-women-from-the-continent/ \"'New Daughters of Africa' Is a Powerful Collection of Writing by Women from the Continent\"], ''Wanted''.</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''These Bones Will Rise Again'' (Indigo Books, 2017) \u2013 a mixture of memoir and historical essay exploring nation-building in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theindigopress.com/these-bones-will-rise-again|title=These Bones Will Rise Again|website=The Indigo Press|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n*''Sweet Medicine'' (Blackbird Books, 2015) \u2013 a novel exploring the 2008 economic crisis in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afripopmag.com/2015/10/19/excerpt-zimbabwean-writer-panashe-chigumadzis-debut-novel-sweet-medicine/|title=AfriPop! - What's New and Whats Next in Global African Culture|date=2015-10-19|website=AfriPop! - What's New and Whats Next in Global African Culture|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n*''Beautiful Hair for Landless People'' (forthcoming)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iwp.uiowa.edu/writers/panashe-chikumadzi|title=CHIGUMADZI, Panashe {{!}} The International Writing Program|website=iwp.uiowa.edu|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n* [[K. Sello Duiker]] Literary Prize in 2016 for ''Sweet Medicine''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2019/04/remembering-k-sello-duiker-great-writer-of-south-africas-post-apartheid-generation-who-would-have-been-45-this-month/|title=Remembering K Sello Duiker, Great Writer of South Africa's Post-Apartheid Generation, Who Would Have Been 45 This Month|date=2019-04-19|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n* [[Ruth First]] Journalism Fellowship, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://witsvuvuzela.com/2015/08/14/a-racy-topic-for-ruth-first/|title=A racy topic for Ruth First|last=Dzonzi|first=Thembisile|date=2015-08-14|website=Wits Vuvuzela|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Reception ===\nChiumadzi's work has been studied widely, particularly within post-colonial studies. Her writing on the use of charms in ''Sweet Medicine'' led to further studies on healthcare and traditional practices in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stobie|first=Cheryl|date=2018-07-03|title=Charms, Blessings and Compromises: Black Women's Bodies and Decolonization in Panashe Chigumadzi's Sweet Medicine|journal=English Academy Review|volume=35|issue=2|pages=37\u201353|doi=10.1080/10131752.2018.1523983|issn=1013-1752}}</ref> Her focus on strong female characters living in economic precarity has been explored in terms of their religious beliefs and the reflection they may give to contemporary life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ndlovu|first=Isaac|date=2016-07-02|title=Politically induced economic precarity, syncretism and female representations in Chigumadzi's Sweet Medicine|journal=Agenda|volume=30|issue=3|pages=96\u2013103|doi=10.1080/10130950.2016.1251227|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nChigumadzi was born in Zimbabwe and grew up in South Africa. She studied at [[University of the Witwatersrand|University of the Witwatersrand;]] while there she was part of the \"Transform Wits Movement\", which called for significant changes to southern Africa's universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailyvox.co.za/transform-wits-lower-tuition-fees-change-of-curriculum-and-better-treatment-of-workers/|title=Transform Wits: lower tuition fees, change of curriculum and better treatment of workers|last=Pilane|first=Pontsho|date=2015-04-13|website=The Daily Vox|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> As part of her doctoral study at the Hutchins Center for African and African American Research at [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africa.harvard.edu/event/symposium-writing-beyond-mugabes-zimbabwe|title=Symposium: Writing Beyond \"Mugabe's Zimbabwe\"|website=africa.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> she has written about the [[Rhodes Must Fall]] protests she witnessed at University of the Witwatersrand.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Panashe Chigumadzi|date=2016|title=Small Deaths|journal=Transition|issue=121|pages=148\u2013163|doi=10.2979/transition.121.1.26|jstor=10.2979/transition.121.1.26}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n[http://www.panashechigumadzi.com/bio Panashe Chigumadzi website]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chigumadzi, Panashe}}\n[[Category:Women writers (modern period)]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean writers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Lajmmoore", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panashe_Chigumadzi"}
